    "answer": "# Task framing\n\n**Problem:** The system prompts embedded in the `RelayStages` class (used as LLM instructions across all stages of the Visual Relay pipeline) contain Visual Relay-specific idioms, most notably `./visual-relay check` in the review stage's prompt. Since Visual Relay is a cross-repository automation framework, its system prompts should be tool-agnostic \u2014 they should describe *what work the sub-agent should do* in general terms, not reference the orchestrator that invoked them. Any Visual Relay-specific jargon leaks the implementation detail of the tool itself into prompts that are consumed by LLMs on behalf of arbitrary repositories.\n\n**Scope of work needed:**\n\n1. **Locate all system prompts** \u2014 in `RelayStages.cs` (and any related files like `TargetedTestCommandTests.SystemPrompt.cs` and `CodingStageSystemPromptTests.cs`) to audit each for VR-specific idioms.\n2. **Identify offending phrases** \u2014 anything naming Visual Relay, `./visual-relay`, `vr-*` commands, or describing the orchestration layer rather than the work the sub-agent should perform.\n3. **Rewrite only those phrases** \u2014 replace them with generic, tool-agnostic alternatives. The user explicitly wants minimal changes, not a full prompt overhaul.\n4. **Update test assertions** that verify prompt content so they match the new generic wording.\n\nThe known offender (`./visual-relay check` in the review step) suggests a pattern where prompts were written with the assumption that the LLM knows it's running inside Visual Relay. The fix is to describe actions in terms of the target repository's conventions (e.g., \"run the project's test suite and report failures\" instead of \"run `./visual-relay check`\").\n\n---\n\n## Solution options\n\n**Option A \u2014 Targeted keyword scrub (minimal touch)**  \nSearch through all system prompt strings for Visual Relay-specific keywords (`./visual-relay`, `vr-`, `Visual Relay`, `VR's`) and rewrite each occurrence to a generic equivalent. Keep every other word identical. This is the smallest diff and easiest to review, but risks missing context-dependent idioms that aren't simple keyword matches (e.g., a sentence like \"The review command has passed\" that implicitly assumes VR is the caller).\n\n**Option B \u2014 Abstraction layer: inject context instead of hardcoding**  \nReplace hardcoded VR-specific commands in prompts with a template placeholder (e.g., `{{verify_command}}`) that gets resolved at invocation time from the stage's configuration (the `Commands` whitelist or a new `PromptVariables` dictionary). This makes prompts fully generic while keeping the LLM correctly informed about which command to run. More upfront refactoring, but future-proof \u2014 no more hardcoding leaks.\n\n**Option C \u2014 Per-stage prompt audit with semantic rewrite**  \nRead each system prompt end-to-end and assess whether its instructions assume the LLM is an agent inside Visual Relay vs. an agent working on the repository. Rewrite where the framing assumes VR-specific context (e.g., \"You are an expert Visual Relay sub-agent\" \u2192 \"You are an expert working on this codebase\"). This catches subtle framing issues that keyword search misses, at the cost of slightly more changes than Option A.\n\n```json\n{ \"summary\": \"Audit all system prompts in RelayStages for Visual Relay-specific idioms (like `./visual-relay check`) and replace them with generic, tool-agnostic alternatives so prompts are portable across repositories. The known offender is in the review-stage prompt; a full audit across all stages is needed to catch any other VR-specific references.\", \"options\": [\"A \u2014 Targeted keyword scrub (minimal touch): search-and-replace VR-specific terms with generic equivalents, smallest diff.\", \"B \u2014 Abstraction layer with template placeholders: replace VR-specific commands with {{verify_command}}-style placeholders resolved at invocation time, more refactoring but future-proof.\", \"C \u2014 Per-stage semantic audit: read each prompt end-to-end and rewrite any framing that assumes VR-specific context, catches subtle issues keyword search misses.\"] }\n```",
